  <!-- ── THE PROBLEM ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="problem" id="problem">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="problem-content">
        <div class="problem-text" data-a>
          <span class="section-label">The Problem</span>
          <h2 class="section-heading">The bottleneck isn't capability</h2>
          <p class="section-sub">
            Most projects aren't set up for agents. There's no declared workflow,
            no structured context, no role boundary, no durable record of decisions.
            Agents landing in these environments must guess, infer from scattered files,
            or ask repeated clarifying questions.
          </p>
          <p class="section-sub" style="margin-top:0.75rem">
            The bottleneck isn't capability — it's the operating environment.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-list">
          <div class="problem-item" data-a data-d="1">
            <svg class="problem-icon" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M18 10a8 8 0 11-16 0 8 8 0 0116 0zm-7 4a1 1 0 11-2 0 1 1 0 012 0zm-1-9a1 1 0 00-1 1v4a1 1 0 102 0V6a1 1 0 00-1-1z" clip-rule="evenodd"/>
            </svg>
            <p><strong>No session memory.</strong> Every new session arrives cold. Conventions, decisions, and context must be re-established every time.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="problem-item" data-a data-d="2">
            <svg class="problem-icon" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M18 10a8 8 0 11-16 0 8 8 0 0116 0zm-7 4a1 1 0 11-2 0 1 1 0 012 0zm-1-9a1 1 0 00-1 1v4a1 1 0 102 0V6a1 1 0 00-1-1z" clip-rule="evenodd"/>
            </svg>
            <p><strong>No role boundaries.</strong> One agent plans, implements, and reviews its own work — with no structural friction or second perspective.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="problem-item" data-a data-d="3">
            <svg class="problem-icon" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M18 10a8 8 0 11-16 0 8 8 0 0116 0zm-7 4a1 1 0 11-2 0 1 1 0 012 0zm-1-9a1 1 0 00-1 1v4a1 1 0 102 0V6a1 1 0 00-1-1z" clip-rule="evenodd"/>
            </svg>
            <p><strong>No workflow authority.</strong> The sequence of work is implicit. Nothing enforces completeness, handoffs, or closure checks.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="problem-item" data-a data-d="4">
            <svg class="problem-icon" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
              <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M18 10a8 8 0 11-16 0 8 8 0 0116 0zm-7 4a1 1 0 11-2 0 1 1 0 012 0zm-1-9a1 1 0 00-1 1v4a1 1 0 102 0V6a1 1 0 00-1-1z" clip-rule="evenodd"/>
            </svg>
            <p><strong>No feedback loop.</strong> Friction from completed work never improves the defaults for the next flow.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── CORE BET ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="core-bet" id="core-bet">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="core-bet-inner" data-a>
        <span class="section-label">The Core Bet</span>
        <div class="core-bet-quote">
          <p>
            The quality of agent output is determined more by the quality of the
            project's harness — its structure, workflow, memory, verification, and
            feedback loops — than by the capability of the agent alone.
          </p>
        </div>
        <p class="core-bet-tagline">
          <strong>A well-harnessed project makes a good agent reliable.</strong><br/>
          A poorly harnessed project makes a great agent guess.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

